Agree with @christianpaquin: 1 _conceptually_ different algorithm per family also was my thinking. So maybe keep (frodo)_shake and _aes variants, but certainly not more than 1 from `sidhp...` and `sikep...`. 

But I see a bigger issue now when looking at this code: With this, we really completely remove algorithms from `openssl` usage -- which isn't so great given what we currently have (the ability to run all candidates side by side, e.g., in performance as well as further downstream app tests, also against classic crypto of the same level). 

So what about this proposal (maybe now, maybe later): Create 3 different lists instead of only 1 (`eccurves_default`), say `ecccurves_level1` (& _2,_3) and make them "run-time activatable", e.g. by switching this OpenSSL code
```
        if (s->ext.supportedgroups == NULL) {
            *pgroups = eccurves_default;
            *pgroupslen = OSSL_NELEM(eccurves_default);
        } else {
```
suitably, e.g., to something like this
```
        if (s->ext.supportedgroups == NULL) {
            switch (atoi(getenv("NIST_STRENGTH_LEVEL"))) { // or some command line option?
            2: 
               *pgroups = eccurves_level2;
               *pgroupslen = OSSL_NELEM(eccurves_level2);
               break;
            3: 
               *pgroups = eccurves_level3;
               *pgroupslen = OSSL_NELEM(eccurves_level3);
               break;
            default:
               *pgroups = eccurves_level1;
               *pgroupslen = OSSL_NELEM(eccurves_level1);
            }
        } else {
```
I'd actually also suggest to put the classic algorithms onto the same "strength" list(s): e.g., "X25519" on _level1, "X448" on _level2 (or 3) to permit running the whole openssl -- and all downstream apps at a specific strength level -- classic as well as PQ crypto.
